      "justification": "Given a known target mass, \\(d\\) is just a re-expression of closeness between \\(m_q\\) and powers of \\(\\mathcal F\\). Reporting that \\(d\\) is near 2 or 3 does not add new statistical evidence. This does not by itself invalidate the calculations, but it risks overstating support."
    },
    {
      "finding": "Uncertainty treatment is incomplete because the comparison uncertainty is dominated by experimental/lattice input on the quark mass, while the dominant source of inferential uncertainty—the a posteriori choice of relation—is omitted entirely.",
      "severity": "MAJOR-REVISION",
      "justification": "The error budget in Table 1 only propagates RG and input uncertainties, yielding an apparently tiny normalized residual. But the real uncertainty in claiming a new mass relation is methodological, not metrological. Omitting this source makes the '0.01σ' framing misleading and could substantially change the interpretation of the result."
    },
    {
      "finding": "The claim that the observations are 'falsifiable' is overstated because the relation can be tested only after choices were made with knowledge of existing data, and the manuscript does not specify a prospective testing protocol.",
